# 🚀 Day 33 – File Transfer Using SCP & FTP

## 📌 Overview
Today I explored how to transfer files between Linux systems using SCP and FTP.

File transfer is important for:
- Uploading configuration files
- Deploying applications
- Taking backups
- Moving logs between servers

---

# 🔐 1️⃣ SCP (Secure Copy)

SCP uses SSH protocol for secure file transfer.

## Copy file from local to remote

```bash
scp filename username@server_ip:/destination/path

Example:

scp test.txt uday@192.168.1.20:/home/uday/


---

Copy file from remote to local

scp username@server_ip:/path/to/file .

Example:

scp uday@192.168.1.20:/home/uday/test.txt .


---

Copy entire directory

scp -r foldername username@server_ip:/destination/path


---

📦 2️⃣ FTP (File Transfer Protocol)

FTP allows file transfer but is NOT encrypted by default.


---

Install FTP Server (RHEL / CentOS)

sudo yum install vsftpd

Start and enable service:

sudo systemctl start vsftpd
sudo systemctl enable vsftpd


---

Connect to FTP Server

ftp server_ip


---

🔎 Basic FTP Commands

Command	Description

ls	List files
get filename	Download file
put filename	Upload file
cd directory	Change directory
bye	Exit FTP



---

⚠ Security Note

FTP traffic is not encrypted.

SCP is secure because it uses SSH.

In production, prefer SCP or SFTP over FTP.



